                        <provenance type="found" when="1872">Discovered by a farmer while ploughing a field in 1872 and later appropriated by him as a gate post (Brash 1879, 160-161). According to Brash (1879, 160-161), the stone formed a lintel in a possible long cist grave (<q>5ft. long, 3ft. 6in. broad and 3ft. deep</q>). However, Quarry (1896,382) later revisited to purchase the stone and asked the landowner to dig on the site again in the hope of finding more ogham stones. This uncovered a stone-lined underground chamber <q>about eighteen feet in length, five feet in width and five in depth</q>, which suggests a souterrain.
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">Purchased by the Royal Irish Academy (Quarry 1896, 382) and now part of the collection of the National Museum of Ireland and on display in the Museum of Archaeology. The stone was recorded in 3d (using an Artec Leo structured light scanner) in collaboration with the <ref target="https://discoveryprogramme.ie/">Discovery Programme</ref> in February 2023 as part of the OG(H)AM project.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
